{{Infobox rugby team | teamname = Newman | image = Club Newman Crest.svg | imagesize = 110px | location = Benavídez, [[Tigre Partido]], [[Greater Buenos Aires]], [[Argentina]] | countryflag = Argentina | fullname = Club Newman | union = [[Unión de Rugby de Buenos Aires|URBA]] | shortname = | nickname = ''Cardenal'', ''Bordó'' | founded = {{Start date and years ago|df=yes|1979|12|15}} | ground = Brother Timothy O'Brien | url = www.clubnewman.com.ar | president = Juan Matías Mc Cormick | coach = Ramiro Varela | league = [[Torneo de la URBA|Top 12]] | season = 2018 | position = 8° |pattern_la1=_goldborder_2|pattern_b1=_orangecollar|pattern_ra1=_goldborder|leftarm1=990000|body1=990000|rightarm1=990000|shorts1=FFFFFF|socks1=008000 }}
'''Club Newman''' is an [[Argentina|Argentine]] [[sports club]] located in the city of Benavídez of [[Tigre Partido]], [[Greater Buenos Aires]]. The club is mostly known for its [[rugby union]] team, which currently plays in the [[Torneo de la URBA|Top 12]], the first division of the [[Unión de Rugby de Buenos Aires]] league system. Newman's facilities also host other sports such as [[field hockey]], [[association football|football]], [[golf]], [[show jumping]] and [[tennis]].
==History== The club was founded on December 15, 1975, by [[Colegio Cardenal Newman|Cardinal Newman College]] Alumni. The first facilities were located in [[Benavidez]], [[Greater Buenos Aires]]. The college had been established by the order of the Christian Brothers.
In 2004, Newman reached the URBA semi-finals, one of its most important achievements, since they have never won any championships. In 2008, Newman reached the URBA TOP 14 final. In 2012 they reached semi-finals and in 2013 too. Also, they managed to get to other to finals in the National Club tournament, one in 2014 and the last one in 2018.
Notable rugby players who started their careers in Newman include [[Cristián Viel]], [[Agustín Canalda]], Francisco Irrarázabal, [[Felipe Contepomi]], [[Manuel Contepomi]], [[Marcos Ayerza]], Gonzalo Gutierrez Taboada, Miguel Urtubey, Pablo Quirno, Marcos Bollini and [[Agustin Gosio]].
